{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958042501/0244.xml":{"full_text":"THE UNION JOURNAL\u2019S\nEditorial Page\nFriday, April 25, 1958\nBankers Win Strike!\nI\nI\nI\nTHE COUNTRY\u2019S bankers have just\nscored an important victory\u2014for them\nand Ohio\u2019s Senator John W. Bricker\nwas right in there pitchin\u2019 for the bank\ners\u2019 side.\nThe bankers won their fight when the\nSenate voted to increase the interest rates\non GI home loans from 412% to 434%.\nPresident Eisenhower had asked that the\nrate be hiked to 5% because the money\nlenders were not making loans available\nat the lower interest rate.\nThe interest rate hike was part of the\nemergency housing bill passed March 12\nby the Senate. The vital vote came on a\nproposed amendment to eliminate the in\nterest rate increaese. The vote was a tie,\n47-47, but Vice President Nixon broke the\ntie by voting the higher interest rate.\nSen. Long (D. La.) described the inter\nest rate increase as \u201ca price support pro\ngram for money lenders\u201d and Senator\nMonroney (D. Okla, said it would give\nlenders \u201ca billion-dollar bounty.\u201d\nOhio\u2019s junior senator, Frank J. Lau\nsche, voted against the interest rate in\ncrease but he was no match for Bricker,\nthe bankers and Nixon.\nBillions for Bankers\nNot a Cent to Taxpayers\nT\nHE FEDERAL Government\u2019s tight\nmoney policy and high interest rates\nhas cost\u2014and is costing\u2014the country\u2019s\ntaxpayers billions of dollars, a Treasury\nDepartment report shows.\nAlthough the Federal debt as of last\nFebruary was $4.5 billion below the peak\nafter World War II, the interest is $3.1 bil\nlion higher. On March 1, 1946 the Federal\ndebt stood at $279,200,000 00. Interest\nthen was $4,700,000,000. On Feb. 1, 1958\nwhen the Federal debt stood at $274,600,\n000,000, the interest jumped to $7,800,\n000,000.\nFor the past three years interest on\nthe Federal debt has gone upwards while\nthe debt itself has decreased reaping a\nharvest for the bankers.\nOn Jan. 1, 1955 when the Federal debt\nhit its postwar peak of $280,800,000, the\ninterest taxpayers were paying to service\nit was $6,800,000,000.\nIn the next three years the debt de\ncreased by $6.2 billion But instead of the\ninterest charges decreasing, they rose by\none billion dollars\u2014from $6,800,000,000\nto $7,800,000,000.\nApparently the Eisenhower Adminis\ntration feels that giving taxpayers a $3\nbillion tax cut is inflationary. But that\nisn\u2019t the case when you turn that amount\nof money over to the bankers. Some logic!\nSen. Fess Confesses\nWE READ about a speech this week\nthat recalled a revealing drama in\nthe Ohio Senate one evening in March\nof last year.\nA few minutes before the Senate con\nvened that evening, an official of the\nOhio Chamber of Commerce dashed\nbreathlessly into the Senate chambers,\nsignalled nervously to State Sen. Lowell\nFess (R. Yellow Springs) to meet him off\nthe Senate floor. Fess complied.\nFess was told he had the wrong \u201cright\nto-work\" bill and was quickly handed the\nright one, or Chamber-approved one. Sev\neral minutes later the Senate convened\nand Fess introduced, under his name, a\n\u201cright-to-work\u201d bill. It died in committee.\nThis past week, Fess was still showing\nan active interest in such legislation by\nspeaking on behalf of the Chamber\u2019s pres\nent \"right-to-work\u201d campaign before the\nFrontiers Club of Columbus, a Negro pro\nfessional group. This time, however, there\nwas no one around to signal him and he\nlet out several cats that the Ohio Chamber\nhas been trying desperately to keep in the\nbag.\nAlthough the Chamber has been on the\nverge of an Academy Award for its role\nas an innocent bystander in the present\ncampaign, Fess pushed it right onto the\nORGANIZE TOLEDO 100%\nOfficial Publication of Organized Labor\nin Northwestern Ohio\nBOR nos\nocsnt10\nGrand\nAward\nW inner\n0\nEntered at Toledo, Ohio, Post Office as second\nclass matter under the act of Aug. 24, 1912\nPublished Every Friday\nPublishing Office, 425 Winthrop Street\nToledo, Ohio\nFor Information Phone CH. 1-9124\nWalter Murphy\nBernard Stern\nWilliam Borden\nDerele Collins\nMelvin Zimkowski,\nEditor\nAssociate Editor\nSports Editor\nCirculation Manager\nEdmond A. Pawlick! Journal Cameramen\nWalter Murphy, Charles Ballard,\nOtto Beebe (Local 348) Board of Trustees\nDave Huber\nDirector of Advertising\nTelephone Advertising Department\nCH. 4-4406 and CH. 6-1141\nMember Trade Union Advertising, N. Y.\nmiddle of the stag when he told the Fron\ntiers Club:\n\u201cI went to set the record straight,\nthe Chamber of Commerce is sponsoring\nthe right-to-work issue.\u201d\nThen, according to a story on the Sena\ntor\u2019s speech in The Ohio Sentinel of Co\nlumbus, Fess was asked a number of ques\ntions. He was asked: Doesn\u2019t it stand to\nreason that the Chamber would not be\nsponsoring this issue unless it was de\nsigned and calculated to benefit and pro\ntect the interests of the organizations\nwhich it represents?\nFess replied: \u201cI\u2019m afraid I will have\nto say that is true\nIn brief then, Fess confirmed what\nOrganized Labor has been saying right\nalong: That the Ohio Chamber of Com\nmerce is the one behind the \u201cright-to\nwork\u201d proposal; that it is not designed to\nhelp the worker, as claimed; that it is cal\nculated to serve the anti-labor interests\nof the Ohio Chamber of Commerce.\nThank you, Senator Fess'\nRight to Sabotage\nAS THE 1958 \u201cright-to-work\u201d cam\npaigns work up to a new hysterical\npitch in a number of highly industrialized\nstates, it is becoming increasingly evident\nthat business itself is becoming a victim\nof professional hucksters and cynical op\nportunists.\nThe objectives of the \"right-to-work\u201d\nproponents are simply to weaken and ul\ntimately to destroy the trade union move\nment as an effective force in the continu\ning fight to give the worker a fair share\nof the wealth he produces.\nBut in that effort they are exposing to\nfatal injury the structure of labor-man\nagement relations carefully built up by\nunions and enlightened employers over\nthe past 50 years.\nThe free American trade union move\nment is a major foundation on which the\nnation\u2019s dynamic economy rests. If the\nworkers themselves had not built it and\nmaintained it, employers and government\nwould have been forced to erect a substi\ntute.\nSo long as labor stands in the front\nranks of democracy defending the rights\nof free men and free institutions it will\nbe the target of self-seeking reactionary\ngroups. If the sad day were ever to arrive\nwhen it failed in that duty, then there\nwould be precious little freedom or free\nenterprise left to defend.\nTarnished Silver Lining\nTHE ADMINISTRATION is misleading\nA the American people in its efforts to\nput a silver lining in the dark clouds of\nthe current recession.\nIt contends that the March unemploy\nment figures are \u201cencouraging,\u201d that they\nshow a \u201cslowing up of the decline.\u201d\nThere\u2019s nothing encouraging about\nadding another 25,000 persons to the un\nemployment rolls in a month that nor\nmally produces a 200,000 drop in jobless\nness.\nThere\u2019s not much slowing up in fig\nures showing steel production at 48.6 per\ncent of capacity or automobile production\noff about 225,000 cars for March.\nThere\u2019s no silver lining in an economic\nsituation that finds 1,446,000 people out of\nwork 15 weeks or longer as of mid-March\nor nine states with insured unemployment\nexceeding 10 percent.\nThe nation\u2019s economy is dangerously\nill. The remedy is strong, decisive action\non an immediate tax cut for lower and\nmiddle income groups, an action that\nshould originate with the Administration.\nThis will prove a more fruitful field\nthan trying to tack silver lining into\nclouds that refuse to disappear.\nThrough The Years\nWith The Toledo Union Journal\nFIFTEEN YEARS AGO\nAPRIL 23, 1943: Charges that the CIO has\nbeen raiding AFL plants was refuted most\nempatically on April 18, when employes of the\nSave Electric Co. met at the TIUC headquar\nters to hold an indignation meeting against the\nAFL CIO President Phillip Murray called\nfor a fight to roll prices back to their Sept. IS,\n1942 level and to eliminate unreasonable war\nprofits because if inflation runs amok, wages\ncan never hope to keep pace.\nTEN YEARS AGO\nAPRIL 23, 1948: Walter P. Reuther, UAW\nCIO president who was shot in his home last\nnight by a sneak assassin was reported recov\nering in Grace Hospital following an operation\non his arm and chest Sandusky became a\nnew UAW-CIO stronghold when the CIO-Uni\nted Auto Workers won plant elections by a\ndecisive majority at the General Motors New\nDeparture and Armour and Co. plants.\nFIVE YEARS AGO\nAPRIL 24, 1953: $24,929.53 has been donat\ned to the Local 12 Summer Camp for Children\nfor expansion and improvements Odland\nIron Unit won provisions in the new contract\nwhich provide a 10 cent an hour wage boost\nand area pension plan to become effective\nSept. 1, 1953 American Floor Surfacing\nUnit members are entering their ninth week of\na strike for a wage boost, settlement of in\nequities, insurance program, area pension and\nrecognition of skilled trade workers.\nYour Money\nOur\nDecision!\nMTMPT\"\"\"\"IFY!\"TVMMITTFMHT\":TVIIIITT\"\"TIMIMr\u201cHIITT\"I\u2014\nThink It Over\nMMffliMllllllMihHW\nIs It The Bottom?\nBy PETE ZVARA\nmoaaszersiztyrzasadsacitmasikaaspgrepgptcAtimcscmeccdgegaletrmmmidrs@ramgusan\"sftl-sslsadaleqlltaillll/lLAlLla*l11Zc1Z12073c1277171802121*ciNAlil,ni7lU\"Btindiim*mumun**mm*...\nTHE OTHER MORNING, while listening to\nthe eight o\u2019clock radio newscasts, as I\nusually do, I heard something that made me\nlook up from my Coffee to ask my wife if she\nhad heard what I had just heard. She nodded\nand looked a bit amused, almost as if to say,\nstatement\ncome\nfrom\nsuch a\n\u201ccould such a\nperson?\"\nPete Zvars\nThis is what we heard, and\nyou did too if you were lis\ntening to the same newscast.\nCommerce Secretary Weeks\nstated in Washington to a re\nporter that he believed we\nhad reached the bottom of\nour current recession and\nthat April will be better\nthan March was.\n\"This recession will pass\njust as soon as people will\nstart buying again,\u201d the re\nporter quoted Mr. Weeks.\nNow there is a profound statement if I\never heard one. That\u2019s just like telling a sick\npatient in a hospital that he will be permitted\nto go home just as soon as he gets well.\nWhat Mr. Weeks should tell (1) the job\nless millions is where they can get the money\nwith which they can buy the endless number\nof things that they need and could use, and\n(2) tell the rest of the people that they have\nnothing to worry about, that their jobs are\nsecure and, therefore, they can go ahead and\nspend what little money they have soaked\naway for the so-called proverbial \u201crainy day.\u201d\nAnyway, as I mused over this gem of Mr.\nWeeks, I couldn\u2019t help but recall another\nstatement that was once made by President\nCalvin Coolidge in one of his rare presidential\npronouncements dealing with unemployment.\n\"When workers are thrown out of work,\u201d\nPresident Coolidge reportedly said, \"unem\nployment results.\u201d\nWELL, I DON\u2019T know whether we have\nreached the bottom of the current recession or\nnot. I don't believe Mr. Weeks knows either.\nBut I sure do hope that he is right and that\nwe did, indeed, touch bottom.\nI\nUnfortunately, there are endless signs that\nwould indicate that Mr. Weeks is simply whist\nling in the dark. For I am afraid that it will\ntake more than just pious wishes, however\nsincere, to get our economy back on its feet\nto put our people back to work again\nwhere they should be.\nSo far, as President Truman and others\nhave said\u2014including Rockefeller, of all peo\nple the government has done practically\nnothing to bolster our economy and help it\nback to normalcy.\nNothing, that is, outside of issuing endless\nstatements about how sound\u2014basically\u2014our\neconomy is. In actuality President Eisenhower\n1 and the people around him are doing their\nlevel best to do a* little as possible in the hope\nthat the recession will somehow, perhaps by\nsome magic, disappear and good times will be\nback again.\nWell, that would be nice, but we don't\nbelieve that such magic will work in twen\ntieth-century America. When our economy is\nlimping and manifests so many signs of illness,\nremedies are called for. Just like in the case\nof any other type of sickness. Meanwhile,\npie are hungry\u2014including kids\u2014while\nR:\nlions of others are worried sick about what\nmight happen to them to their jobs and\ntheir future.\nRight now, how many American families\nare worried sick about their mortgaged homes\nabout their automobiles and a thousand\nand one other items that they bought on the\ninstallment plan?\nThese conditions are inexcusable in Amer-\nica today where we have more than enough\nfor everyone\u2014if we can only learn how to\nmanage our affairs properly and as they should\nbe.\nTHIS IS THE time of year when normally\nour economy is booming when people\nshould lie really working at good jobs paying\ngood wages. But a quick glance through our\nmagazines and newspapers tell us that condi\ntions are just the opposite\nThe steel industry, which should be clip\ning along at a high rate of production now, is'\nhitting new lows. Current operating capacity\nis listed as being around 45%, with the result\nthat our steeltowns are experiencing near\ndepression conditions.\nConditions in the auto industry are worse.\nMillions of potential car-buyers are holding\nstill, not buying automobiles simply because\nthey are afraid of tomorrow\n\u201cWe'll just keep the old buggy and see\nwhat happens,\u201d is the usual answer of those\nwho would otherwise be buying cars right\nnow.\nAnd I am afraid that until such time as\nwe are able to eliminate that kind of thinking\nfrom the minds of our people, we are going\nto have trouble.\nTHE PROBLEM, of course, is how to do\njust that. There are any number of proposals\nalready laid before our government which, if\napplied energetically and massively by Wash\nington, would get us back on the high road to\nprosperity. Among these proposals are:\n1) A large-scale program of useful pub\nlic works projects that would create a lot of\njobs and enrich our country with many things\nthat we need.\n2) Adequate jobless insurance benefits\nto our unemployed to keep them solvent\nto insure their purchasing power to make\nit possible for them to keep up their payments\non their debts, particluarly their mortgage\npayments during the time they are forced to\nbe jobless through no fault of their own.\n3) Cut taxes to enable people to spend\nmore. Certainly this proposal isn\u2019t much of a\nhelp to people who are jobless, but there is no\nquicker way of making more money available\nto those who are still employed so that they\ncan increase their purchases right now when\nthey are most needed.\nThere are many, many other proposals\nthat would help. What's wrong with hiking\npension benefits to our retired and otherwise\ndisabled people? Surely here is one field\nwhere we know that every cent would be\nspent to buy new things, needed things thus\ncreating more work for our industries.\nAnd what is wrong with a really massive\nprogram of road building? Surely right now\nwe would have the manpower available\nwe would have the steel capacity, cement,\nlumber and everything else that goes into\nsuch a program, including trucks and other\nroad-building vehicles to stimulate our eco\nnomy. There is no question, but that we need\nendless thousands of miles of new multiple\nlane highways to accomodate our modern\nautomobiles. So, what's holding us up?\nWhat about our schools our city, coun\nty and federal buildings all over our country?\nThe possibilities here are limitless just as\nthe needs of our people are limitless.\nSo, what are we waiting for? Or, perhaps\nI should say, what are we afraid of?\nSurely even a moron can tell that we\nhave all the necessary ingredients to make all\nthis possible to bring about the conditions\nfor a prosperity that Would dazzle the world.\nWell, that is one road that we\u2014and our\nleaders both in government and business\u2014can\nelect to follow.\nAdmittedly, to take such a road requires\nvision and courage of the highest order. Little\nmen, timid and weak, will never take that\nroad.\nBut what about the other road\u2014for there\nis an \u201cother\u201d road for our country to follow.\nThat is the road, I am afraid, that will lead us\nto continued and increased suffering to\nfear of tomorrow to indecision and event\nually economic chaos and black deepair.\nThat is the road that will quickly lead us\nto another situation when, with straight faces\nand cynical smiles, the leaders of the Soviet\nUnion will once again invite us to hold a\nworld-wide economic conference to \u201chelp solve\nunemployment* in the capitalistic countries.\u201d\nA NEW YORK PSYCHIATRIST re\nceived a postcard from a vacationing pa\ntent \u201cDear Doctor,\u201d it said, \u201cHaving a\nwonderful time. Wish you were here to\ntell me why.\u201d\nIt s Your Washington\nBy WILLARD SHELTON\nTHE \u201cRIGHT\u201d OF a jobless worker \u201cto suffer,\u201d said\nWhite House aide Howard Pyle in a celebrated out\nburst of, candor, is one of the precious rights of the in\ndividual the denial of which by a paternalistic govern\nment would unhinge the structure of freedom.\nPres. Eisenhower would not be so crass as to express things\nthat way, but he has an overmastering aversion to the notion\nthat the government has more than an extremely limited re\nsponsibility about the personal distress of jobless millions.\nThings are bound to look up, he assumes. Anything the\ngovernment does may bring more harm than good (the hobgob\nlins of inflation and horrid budget deficits lie just around the\ncorner). In principle, it is \u201cwrong\u201d for the government to do too\nmuch in any case.\nIn short, the individual\u2019s \u201cright to suffer\u201d must not be un\nduly restricted. He may not realize it, but the Administration\u2019s\nstern refusal to assist him is all intended for the fellow\u2019s own\ngood.\nTHE WHITE HOUSE clearly has begun to fling its weight\naround and to rally Republicans in Congress to check the drive\nof Democrats for anti-recession measures. This helps correct the\nsometimes carelessly-flung accusation that Pres. Eisenhower\n\u201cdoesn't know how\u201d to use the enormous power of leadership\ninherent in his office.\nHe does know how. The point is that for more than five\nyears he has shown he is disinclined to exert the power except\nfor negative causes\nWhen the original flexible-farm-price bill was driven\nthrough, the White House mounted a lobbying campaign in full\nsupport of Agriculture Sec. Ezra Taft Benson\u2019s program. There\nwere telephone calls from the White House and direct ap\nproaches by White House staff members to doubtful or wavering\ncongressmen. This was an affirmative action\u2014a campaign for\nsomething\u2014but it was one in which the President was deeply\ninterested.\nSince then, he has been deeply interested chiefly in things\nhe wants to defeat.\nIn a Congress where the party balance is nearly even, the\nveto threat is itself enough to check action. The President is\nusing vetoes and veto threats to force Democrats to pull in\ntheir horns.\nHe is using them to tell Republicans that in doubtful cases\nthey would be well advised not to break with him. So GOP\nmembers who were almost demoralized earlier in the session,\nlacking any conviction that would let them present a united\nfront against Democratic proposals, are now voting more fre\nquently on party lines\nWHEN EISENHOWER FAILS to use his powers to get\nsomething he has formally asked, the assumption must be that\nhe really prefers not to get it.\nWe had an example last session when the President pre\ntended he \u201cdidn\u2019t know\u201d that House Republicans deserted in\ngreat masses the precise aid-to-education program he had de\nmandedi\nIt wasn\u2019t believable, of course, that the White House\n\u201cdidn\u2019t know\u201d about the showdown vote. The point is that\nEisenhower had changed his mind without publicly disclosing\nit. He didn\u2019t really want a federal aid-to-education bill of any\nkind although he campaigned in 1956 on the promise that he\nwould get it.\nThe proof? Six months later Eisenhower formally\ndropped the request for federal school aid. It disappeared\nfrom his program.\nAs of now, Eisenhower on recession policy is a clear win\nner over Congress. He has forced the Democrats to slow down\non public works, he has an agreement from them not to \u201cjump\nthe gun\u201d on tax cuts, and he is running things.\nLetters To The Editor\nProfits to Blame\nTO THE EDITOR:\nHow right Reuther was that\nexcess profits, and not wages\nto labor, are to blame for this\ndepression we are in.\nLack of buying power is the\nbad wolf.\nThe big steel companies got\n$6 a ton they said was neces\nsary to make up the raise to\nlabor The Chamber of Com\nmerce that has always been\nopposed to labor, after a com\nplete study said $3 a ton was\nenough.\nNow on the local field, last\nyear I had some plumbing\ndone. The company charged\nme $5 an hour for the plumber\nthey sent to do the work.\nAbout six weeks ago I again\nhad the same company do\nsome work and the bill was\nfor $6 and hour.\nI inquired, and found the\ncompany had raised their\nplumbers 35 cents an hour, so\ntheir new charge should have\nbeen $5.35 an hour. But they\ntook the 65 cents an hour and\ndidn\u2019t even say thanks.\nSo you have the national\nand the city situations, and\nyou will find all in between\nthe same.\nJ BARTHOLOMEW\n302 Amber Court\nBulletin Board\nI\nSaturday, April 26\nKIDS PARTY 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nGOODFELLOWS PARTY 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nACKLIN 10:00 A.M. Parlor H\nSunday, April 27\nNATIONAL SUPPLY 10:00 A.M. Parlor A*\nMonday, April 28\nCONVENTION DELEGATES 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nSTANDARD EQUIPMENT\nOFFICE 5:00 P.M. Parlor C\nCITY MACHINE 10 A.M. Parlor B\nTuesday, April 29 m\nNONE SCHEDULED\nWednesday, April 36\nNONE SCHEDULED\nThursday, May 1\nCHAMPION 11:30 A.M. Parlor A\nCHAMPION \u20147:30 P.M.\u2014 Parlor A\nSAVE ELECTRIC 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nCAMERA CLUB 8:00 P.M. Parlor C\nCAMP COUNSELLORS 7:00 P.M. Parlor H\nFORT PITT 8:00 P.M. Room 309\n\nFriday, May 2\nWILLYS (NIGHT) 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nWILLYS (DAY) 8:00 P.M. Scott High\nAUTO LITE STEWARDS 2:30 P.M. Parlor A\nSTEEL TUBE\nELECTION 2:30 to 5:00 P.M. Parlor B\nRATHBUN JONES 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nAMERICAN FLOOR 8:00 P.M. Parlor C\nACME 8:00 P.M. Parlor H\nBUCKEYE PAINT 8:00 P.M. Conference Room\nOTHER LOCAL VMON MEETINGS\nNEWSPAPER PRESSMEN\n4th Friday 7:30 P.M. Kapp\u2019s Hall\nPRINTING PRESSMEN ASSISTANTS NO. 55\n4th Friday 612 1 Huron St.\nALLIED PRINTING TRADES COUNCIL\n1st Friday 612% Huron St","height":"26960","width":"19580"}}
